27:29.204 --> 27:52.887
involved too much of a problem for the city and also 
messed up the,

27:29.204 --> 27:52.887
supposedly took occupied,

27:29.204 --> 27:52.887
widely needed facilities for the commercial 
airlines and other political reasons. I guess at

27:53.204 --> 27:57.211
the closest I came, really, to locking horns with a 
politician. But I kept my temper, and I'm glad I

27:58.013 --> 28:01.519
did. But if I ever did dislike the congressman, the 
congresswoman, the senator, that was the one. You

28:12.480 --> 28:13.782
thought she was unreasonable? I thought she was 
wrong. Of course, she had her political reasons,

28:18.736 --> 28:31.010
and I understand the power of politics, but I had my 
military responsibilities.

28:31.030 --> 28:41.581
You remained in that job for about two years, and 
then you shifted to the 28th Air Division in

28:31.030 --> 28:41.581
California, Hamilton Air Force Base. Why'd they 
shift you?

28:45.786 --> 28:46.887
I'd been up there for couple of years, and after 
you've been in the command for a while, you know,

28:47.153 --> 28:51.760
maybe look forward to going to another one. But I 
loved California, and Hamilton Air Force Base was

28:51.780 --> 29:00.652
the most choice air base in the entire United 
States. Why? One of the most beautiful,

29:00.792 --> 29:08.924
convenient, to that lovely city of San Francisco. 
Climate-wise, it was better than that rainy area

29:08.944 --> 29:16.755
of Northwest United States and Washington, but 
beautiful. and also I was very close to General

29:17.258 --> 29:42.321
Parker who was then the commander of Western Air 
Defense Force who commanded the three divisions

29:17.258 --> 29:42.321
from the north to the south and he and I were very 
close mutually respected each other and that job

29:17.258 --> 29:42.321
came open and we liked each other and He knew I loved 
Hamilton. I'd done a good job, and I'd been up in

29:45.360 --> 29:54.048
Washington for two years, and the way things go, he 
gave me the job. Well, either at Hamilton or on my

29:54.488 --> 30:00.434
board in Washington, were there any major 
problems that you had to overcome? No.

30:01.996 --> 30:04.899
Essentially, this was the same type of job, 
exactly. It was a similar type of an air division,

30:04.979 --> 30:10.384
but in a different location.

30:11.208 --> 30:17.919
You felt a little bit greater responsibility for 
protecting, let's say, a huge area like San

30:11.208 --> 30:17.919
Francisco versus, let's say, Seattle. But on the 
other hand, Seattle had terrific aircraft

30:17.939 --> 30:21.465
industry. And SAC bases in it. Of course, now I had 
SAC bases protecting the 28th Division area. So

30:26.954 --> 30:30.720
really, it's essentially exactly the same job. I 
was living closer to my boss, my headquarter, as a

30:30.740 --> 30:34.507
matter of fact, on the same airbag. He would come 
over and see me and give me

30:51.050 --> 30:52.191
of proper management. Same job. As a matter of 
fact, I felt much more secure because of the

30:54.614 --> 31:03.182
experience of wearing my star for a few years in the 
Command and Air Division. I took over the 28th

31:03.202 --> 31:06.906
without a problem. As a matter of fact, it was a 
little bit smaller in size and units and radar

31:06.926 --> 31:17.076
sites in the 25th Air Division. And I didn't have 
the Canadians under me then.

31:23.922 --> 31:28.389
How did you get along with the Canadians when you 
were in Washington? Fine. Typical great people.

31:33.476 --> 31:38.483
Well, were you sorry to leave Hamilton in October 
1960 when you went to Italy for three years? No, I

31:38.764 --> 31:45.253
figured I was due for an overseas assignment.

31:46.195 --> 31:49.980
Here again, when I came up, I had a chance to take my 
family. And here again, see, it was a NATO job. It

31:55.028 --> 31:56.089
was combined. It was shape. Shape. And here I see I 
was in a combined command. I was wearing a NORAD

32:01.054 --> 32:02.316
hat. I'd been operating with Canadian forces, 
another nation. I'd had experience a long, long

32:07.461 --> 32:09.163
time. But now you were the deputy commander. Yep. 
And the commander was what, a two-star general?

32:16.690 --> 32:20.254
No, a general.

32:21.331 --> 32:26.158
Bianchi was a lieutenant general, three-star 
general in the Italian Air Force. But he was

32:26.178 --> 32:41.422
commanding the Fifth Allied Tactical Air Force of 
the

32:26.178 --> 32:41.422
southern area of shape. What did we call it? Yeah, 
north, central, and south. South Forces, what

32:44.888 --> 32:53.778
economy is referred to them as South Forces of 
NATO, which included the Army, Navy, and Air

32:44.888 --> 32:53.778
Forces. Greeks, Turks, Italian, American, 
British, you name it, NATO. In a sense, you lost

33:00.546 --> 33:05.311
your own command to a new job. Did you resent losing 
time? I figured this was definitely a step up,

33:07.974 --> 33:11.198
because this was NATO. Sure. This was a... Allied 
Tactical Air Force. I was going to an Air Force

33:17.801 --> 33:22.907
level from a division level, so I was going on. And I 
never dreamed of the problems I would have when I

33:23.167 --> 33:31.177
took over this job. It was a, the move was a 
fantastic journey. We traveled by ship with my

33:37.424 --> 33:44.072
family on a first class USS Independence. First, 
look at TB Love Boat today and see that ship. Well,

33:48.371 --> 33:49.753
that's the type of ship we were on. Had my whole 
family with me and shipped my car and all. Treated

33:53.638 --> 33:54.520
royally. SS in the family. It wasn't an United 
States ship. Well, SS, yeah. And commercial ship.

34:03.993 --> 34:06.516
Big luxury liner. On the way we stopped at 
Casablanca and got ashore. That's the first state

34:12.219 --> 34:17.345
my wife had any foreign country and was aghast at 
it. And then we stopped for a second at Gibraltar,

34:17.806 --> 34:31.384
then on to Majorca, and then to Naples, and then to 
basically Dr. Genova. We met there by accident.

34:33.547 --> 34:44.117
some of the staff that I was taking over, and then we 
drove across in a car to Vicenza, Italy, where I was

34:33.547 --> 34:44.117
there for the next three years. Very interesting 
assignment. Charlie? Yep. Do you want to change

34:46.820 --> 34:48.422
the water? Oh, yeah.

34:52.245 --> 34:59.132
You mentioned problems and all kinds of problems 
in Italy with NATO. What were they? That I hadn't

35:00.347 --> 35:01.509
anticipated. And you had not anticipated? What 
were these problems? Well, upon arriving at

35:04.653 --> 35:29.389
Vicenza, a little town about 30 minutes driving 
west from Venice, in the northern area of Italy,

35:04.653 --> 35:29.389
just at the foothills of the Alps, just an ideal 
place, geographical-wise, in Europe, to be

35:04.653 --> 35:29.389
assigned with my family, naturally. was the 
happiest man in the world. I hadn't been there 24

35:31.657 --> 35:44.615
hours when I met the man I was replacing, and he 
briefed me on his boss, who was to be my boss,

35:31.657 --> 35:44.615
Lieutenant General Bianchi. That is wrong. 
B-I-A-N-C-H-I. If there ever was a Hitler

35:47.719 --> 35:53.347
fascist, this man was. No kidding. The general I 
relieved, a brigadier general, United States Air

35:55.109 --> 35:59.055
Force, That's one reason he was being reassigned, 
and the spot had to be filled, and it was a NATO

35:59.407 --> 36:06.577
assignment. He wouldn't speak to General 
Bianchi. He would not even go into his office. They

36:13.086 --> 36:14.588
hated each other so much. Really? And he briefed me 
on the type of man this gentleman was, and I didn't

36:15.490 --> 36:20.737
know this. Nobody ever told me. And I was shocked. 
They must have known this back at the Pentagon. I'm

36:28.357 --> 36:29.097
sure they did. Why they assigned you? Because 
you'd had so many international contacts? And had

36:34.302 --> 36:40.048
been on combined staff, worked with other 
nationals. So here was another national, a

36:40.068 --> 36:46.875
commander that I was the vice commander on. And of 
course, I learned as time went on that no wonder.

36:52.006 --> 36:54.329
guy wouldn't speak to him, and I don't blame him. 
Had I been a different person, I guess I wouldn't

36:54.349 --> 36:59.355
have spoken with the man. But he hated, there's no 
doubt this man in his heart had to hate Americans

37:01.238 --> 37:12.732
from the standpoint of the typical jealous 
battalion, hating an American. but it stemmed

37:12.914 --> 37:16.218
from his background as a fascist, I'm sure. He was 
the tactical air commander in support of General

37:16.559 --> 37:25.331
Rommel for the African campaign against the 
American and British forces. That's how high a

37:25.351 --> 37:26.833
position he was. How the heck did he ever get a 
position in charge of NATO? Well, actually, in

37:31.159 --> 37:39.990
this position, though, and on through the end of 
the war, you think, why shouldn't he be chief of

37:31.159 --> 37:39.990
staff of the Italian Air Force? And, you know, way 
high up, But he wasn't, and he was only lieutenant

37:41.332 --> 37:43.475
colonel. But it's obvious his personality and 
just

37:43.495 --> 37:59.417
a nasty, nasty, arrogant, fierce, savage man, his 
personality. Not physically, but nasty in his

37:59.437 --> 38:02.060
talk. He could speak perfect English, but proud of 
it. A typical arrogant, strutting, ill-duty

38:06.046 --> 38:09.010
type. I hated his guts. Put that in there. That's 
awfully strong. And

38:16.571 --> 38:25.602
subsequently, of course, I found out that he was 
known all over NATO as a respected person. And your

38:25.622 --> 38:29.246
old Charlie Bond was his vice commander. How did he 
get the job of being in charge of the southern

38:30.188 --> 38:38.878
section of NATO with that personality? He had had 
previous jobs in NATO headquarters, but it's

38:39.365 --> 38:46.172
obviously because of his personality he couldn't 
get along. They didn't want him. But he was a very

38:47.593 --> 38:50.957
capable tactical commander. There's no doubt 
there wasn't another general in the Italian Air

38:51.297 --> 39:01.147
Force that could even touch him in tactical 
experience and know-how. They couldn't. There

39:01.707 --> 39:05.271
was none that I knew of or met that could even touch 
him. He was, no doubt, because of his experience

39:06.112 --> 39:09.437
and background. He had been in the Civil War in 
Spain, on the side of the Pacific. At times he'd get

39:16.767 --> 39:22.896
off on the Il Duce, and no doubt he still respected 
the Il Duce. What did he say about it? He just

39:24.919 --> 39:25.760
respected him. Nothing direct about, I love the 
man, nothing like that, but his conversation

39:28.564 --> 39:35.494
always about the Il Duce was, you know, it was 
obvious that... He's a fascist. How could you

39:38.909 --> 39:40.371
tell? He was a typical, anything you've ever read 
about the arrogant, fascist type of person, this

39:40.411 --> 39:50.283
is the way he acted. You've seen movies of him. 
You've seen movies of Ducey, El Ducey. This is the

39:54.669 --> 39:56.751
way he acted. This was his personality. He would, 
in inspecting troops walking down a line, he'd

39:58.854 --> 40:03.760
actually strut like maybe the way a movie star 
would strut, you know, over, just emoting. You can

40:11.535 --> 40:15.139
tell the way I'm talking how I felt about the man.

40:18.523 --> 40:26.030
My first reception by him was, had I not been told 
about the man, I would have never suspected it the

40:18.523 --> 40:26.030
first time I met him. I was received in his office 
with open arms, very polite, very condescending,

40:34.958 --> 40:41.046
And looking back now, getting ready to shove the 
knife up my rear end and down my back. Literally

40:42.327 --> 40:45.491
hated Americans.

40:46.673 --> 41:00.711
My boss down the line, American Air Force, United 
States Air Force's wife, Lieutenant General

40:46.673 --> 41:00.711
Swafford, who was Commander Air South, actually 
was commander of him, see, in the NATO command.

41:01.452 --> 41:02.653
Commander Air South was the Air Force component of 
AFSAL, which was the southern region of Europe of

41:03.528 --> 41:21.945
the NATO command, vis-a-vis AFSANT, Armed Forces 
Central Europe, and AFNORTH, Armed Forces

41:03.528 --> 41:21.945
Northern Europe. That was NATO, in effect. Then, 
of course, you had some other commands. But

41:25.648 --> 41:27.530
essentially, that was Europe. I was vice 
commander of the 5th Allied Tactical Air Force

41:33.346 --> 42:02.965
under air air force's south general swafford who 
was always an uh american general that's the way

41:33.346 --> 42:02.965
the village were assigned the commander of the 
fifth a-tap was essentially the italian air force

41:33.346 --> 42:02.965
italy so naturally it was italian general the 
commander of the sixth a-tap uh the other air force

41:33.346 --> 42:02.965
of the uh air south was in izmir turkey and uh was 
commanded by a edict, an agreement, by an American

42:03.113 --> 42:10.705
general, American Air Force general. That was a 
lineup. And it consisted of the Greek and Turkish

42:11.526 --> 42:14.791
Air Forces.

42:16.995 --> 42:19.679
Fifth ATF and Sixth ATF. Immediately to our north 
in Central Forces was the Fourth ATF, which was

42:19.940 --> 42:28.513
also commanded by an American Air Force general. 
But that's the way the setup was. Were most of your

42:32.502 --> 42:36.545
problems on this job caused by Bianchi? Oh, 
absolutely. I didn't have any problem whatsoever

42:38.127 --> 42:40.469
in Italy. As far as the job itself was concerned, 
were there any problems, or were they all this man?

42:46.394 --> 42:51.439
Oh, there were some problems in cooperation with 
the Italian Army. I think probably caused by the

42:53.120 --> 42:57.724
feelings of the United States Army component, 
which was really a surface-to-surface missile

42:58.480 --> 43:19.802
unit at Pachinza, a nuclear-tipped outfit, and 
working with an Italian counterpart of the same

42:58.480 --> 43:19.802
type of an outfit, where really they could help 
instruct them and train them and so forth. And they

43:19.822 --> 43:24.066
were the members of the Army forces. of AFSAL, 
Armed Forces of the South. And the Army General of

43:28.934 --> 43:49.715
the Italian Army and General Bianchi, the Air 
Force commander, they had jealousy, very

43:28.934 --> 43:49.715
obvious, much more so than those of, let's say, the 
Army and the Air Force, the United States forces,

43:28.934 --> 43:49.715
let's say, back in the United States. We didn't 
know what professional jealousy was. You see that

43:51.978 --> 43:54.120
over there. But that was their problem, really, 
sir. It wasn't my problem. Administrative-wise,

43:58.431 --> 44:17.673
see, General Bianchi, administration-wise, he 
had nothing to do with me and about 10

43:58.431 --> 44:17.673
or 15, maybe 12, 15 or 20 officers and airmen of the 
United States Air Forces was also assigned to this

43:58.431 --> 44:17.673
headquarters and part of his staff. Essentially, 
The 5th Allied Tactical Air Force was an American

44:20.881 --> 44:26.327
staffed outfit to do the work for NATO. But it was an 
Italian Air Force General that commanded the 5th

44:26.347 --> 44:30.252
General. And the Chief of Staff was an Italian Air 
Force Brigadier General. But the Vice Commander,

44:36.659 --> 44:40.743
number two, was an American General Meade. At that 
time, a Brigadier General. And the slot had always

44:45.068 --> 44:47.331
been a Brigadier General. That's what it called 
for in the organization. Give me some examples of

44:51.205 --> 44:54.229
some of the problems you had with this man. He

44:54.890 --> 45:19.947
didn't like

44:54.890 --> 45:19.947
for my driver to come up in front of the 
headquarters building and let me out. which was

45:21.850 --> 45:26.835
facing the ramp of the little airport we had. He 
didn't like for my driver, for instance, to bring

45:27.555 --> 45:36.364
me up in the morning and let me get out of my car the 
same way his driver brought him up and let him get

45:27.555 --> 45:36.364
out of the car. I didn't know this irritated him for 
about a month. And finally, he just called me in and

45:39.006 --> 45:49.596
told me that he would prefer that I come up in the 
back of the building.

45:50.082 --> 45:53.446
This was really the first time that he directed me 
to do something. It was really a matter of

45:53.526 --> 45:58.252
administration, however it pertained to 
discipline, command, and control. So I didn't

45:58.272 --> 46:01.696
argue with him. And I said, all right. You said, all 
right. Oh, yeah. I didn't argue with him. I said,

46:05.921 --> 46:07.743
OK. OK. But it irritated me. And I turned around and 
walked out of there. I didn't follow this

46:13.971 --> 46:16.474
instruction. Oh, you didn't? No. I got to think 
about it, and I thought, I'm not going to do this.

46:23.302 --> 46:26.185
I'm a deputy commander of this company. And I can 
see now what my forerunner, I forget his name,

46:26.205 --> 46:34.653
general somebody, I can see what he means now. So I 
might as well take the bit in my mouth right at the

46:34.673 --> 46:38.196
outset here. But pretty soon I won't be speaking to 
this guy. So the next day I came up to Barclay

46:41.059 --> 46:46.444
Fronikin and got out of the car. This went on for 
about a week and he'd seen me. Probably one day an

46:50.757 --> 47:00.492
airman comes in,

46:50.757 --> 47:00.492
Comandante Vaughn, General Bianchi would like to 
see you. A very polite aide. So I walked in and I

47:04.539 --> 47:05.500
walked

